### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The sanctions against the school were a punishing blow, and they seemed to what the efforts the school had made to change? Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		The Sanctions _against_ the school were a punising blow,_ and they _seemed to_ what the _efforts the school had made_ to change. But the sanctions might better be described as against the students and faculty who broke the rule.<n><n>Output: the sanctions were a punishing blow to the school and seemed to what the effort the school had made to avoid.<n><n>Square = input...... \.... <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:James was cooling off two quickly.  He would die if he didn't find some way to stop what? Choices:  A: loss of heat B: revenge C: expansion D: relaxation E: calm down<n>Output:		James was cooling off too quickly.  He would freeze if he didn't stop.<n><n># Your Solution Below<n><n>if ( 18 < _ < 6  )<n>{<n>  print ( _(18) 6.022E23 )<n>  print ( _ (18) 6)<n>}<n><n>if _ \ frac { 6 b + 9 c }  = 6<n>{<n>  print "a"<n>  print "b"<n>  print "c"<n>  print "d"<n>  print "e"<n>}<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The president is the leader of what institution? Choices:  A: walmart B: white house C: country D: corporation E: government<n>Output:		The president is the CEO of the company. The ceo is the head who makes decisions. The country is ruled by the president of its government. The government is ruled by president of the country. So The answer will be CEO.<n><n>Input:Which is the largest continent? Choices: A: Europe B: Eurasia C: Africa D: Asia E: America F: Antarctica<n>Output: The largest continent is Asia. Asia is 1/3 of the Earth's land mass. Africa is 30% of the Earth's surface area covered by land. Eurasia is the combined land mass of Europe and Asia, including all of Asia and the northern portion of the African plate. Australia is the smallest and also the only continental state that is an island. The combined continent of Europe and Asia together is the largest at 54,750,000 square miles followed by Africa and the Americas which are nearly equal. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:A fox was thirsty searching for water during the drought, where was he? A,C,E options means injury to the knees, teeth and lips respectively. B means injury to spine etc.<n><n>## Problem Set 09<n>Problem-1<n>#### Instruction:Let there be 300 people and you know that they are having average of 7 children per family. Also, you know that the population grows at a constant rate of 12% per year and the death rate is 2% of total population. If the population of people today is 250, what percent do the deaths have to be in order to maintain population?<n><n>Solution:<n>Let us assume that the total people now are P ( 250 ) and suppose, death rate of the people be D now. So, at that time the population was of DP / (1 - D). We know that the population grows @ 12% per annum so the population will be DP / (1+ 12%D ) + k. Where k is some constant k<n><n>Suppose the population be P1 after D more k years, so the population after D more k years will be<n><n>So,<n><n>\begin{code}<n>      P1 = D P ( 1+ 12D + k - 1) / (1+ 2D) = D P ( 3+ D) (1+k) (1+2D) / (1+2D+k)  = D P * 3 + D (1+k)<n>\end{code}<n><n>Suppose P ( total people ) = x, D ( average, yearly) = x/3, k = 1 then we have P1 = 3x, and so percentage of deaths is 3x / ( 15x – D)<n>Since D is 1, DP ( 1+k) = 15P – 15, where 15 is chosen so that the P be greater than 1, otherwise we will get 0, in that case.<n><n>So the Percentage of deaths are 3 / (15-4) = 28. That is 28% of the people need to die in order to maintain the same % of the total population.<n><n>Problem

Choices:  A: advisory B: mandate C: soap opera D: elective E: optional<n>Output:		The evacuation became mandator. Choices:  A B D E<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where could a fungus grow and not be disturbed by sunlight? Choices:  A: under rocks B: manhattan C: toenails D: grocery store E: fallen tree<n>Output:		A fungus grows and not be disturbed in a grocery store<n>Input:Fred is riding his bike downhill and has reached a speed of 52 miles per hour. He rides around a sharp curve and loses 5/8 of his speed. How long does it take him to stop?<n>Output:f = 52, f - 5/8 = f + f = 52<n>let f = \ frac { t } { d }, \ frac { t + 1 } { d } ;<n>\ frac { t + d } { d } = \ frac a b, \ frac t } { t + b }, d \ b,1, 1 ;<n>c = b, \ frac 2 d }, d =2 d - 1, 1 ; \ frac 2 },<n>\ frac 1 = \ frac 2 \ frac 4 d - 2 d - 1 d t + 4 d - 4 d - 1 d - 2 d + 1 d + 2 d + 4 d + d d d d d d } \ d } \ frac 2 + 1 d } t + d } t, 2  ;<n>\ frac 4 t + 4 d } t.<n>\ frac 3 \ frac b } | x<n>1 = \ frac {\ frac d + 1 } { x } \ frac b } ;<n>1 = \ fract { \ frac {\ fract b } { frac \ frac d } { x } \ } }<n>1 = \ ffrac {\ ffrac x d } { frac b } ; \ frac x d }<n><n>d | x = d | 2 <n>\ fract { d | x } d.<n>t = - \ frac d + d - \ frac d - d <n>t = \ 2 d.<n>d = \ 2( t - 1 ) = \ 2( \ frac t + 1 ).<n><n>d = \ 6.<n>t = d / 2 = \ 3 d = 9.<n>T = d / 6 = 9 d / 6 = \ 9.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What is required to be good at playing tennis? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What state is the John Davis  Lodge toll road found in? Choices:  a:2^46 b:111111 c:true d:false <n>Output:The answer is d because we just multiply 2^34 with 2^35.<n><n>Input: A man is going at a speed of 20km/hr. He moves 15m in the first 1 minute. After that he cycles 5m in 13 seconds. Find the man's speed? Choices: <n>20km/hr, because he travelled 15+5m in 2mins, 15m+5m/2=10+2.5m/2<n>25km/hr, because 25/13<n>40km/hr, this answer is incorrect because speed is measured in km/hr. If speed is decreased, time increases. Here 20km/h was the starting speed. If it was increased to 40km/hr from 20km/hour then time will decrease. This decreased time will offset the increase in speed. This is shown like: (15km+5km)/(60m/55)(16.76kg/hour), 11.3366693360393m/16.76= 645.99334545058m/2=322.996672515226m. But the man moved a total of (15+5=20)m in 42mins of travel. So the correct answer is: 2

Choices:  A: store B: classroom C: backpack D: cabinet E: teacher<n>Output:		student go to store for pencils. <n><n>Input:You need to reach your house,  what do you do? Choices: A: go to the park B: Go to the park C: Go home D: Go back E: Go outside<n>Output:<n>Go to the park is not for reach your house.<n>Go to the park to reach your house<n>So go to the park or go home is to reach your house.<n><n>Input:The boy went to the library to buy a new book. Choices: A: find a good book with good reviews B: go to the store C: look for the bookstore<n>Output:<n>You cannot buy a new book in the Library. You can only read books there.<n><n>### [참고]<n>``` java<n>public class Solution {<n>    public int findTargetSumWays(int[] nums, int S) {<n>        int ans = 0;<n>        if(S < 0) return 0;<n>        Arrays.sort(nums);<n>        int mid = nums.length / 2;<n><n>        if (nums[mid] <= S) ans += nums[mid] == S? 1 : 0;<n>        for (int i = mid + 1; i < nums.length; i++)<n>            if (nums[i] <= S) ans -= (nums[i - 1] + nums[i]) == S? 1  : 0;<n>            ans = nums[i] <=S? ans + (nums[i-1] + nums.length -mid - 1) : ans + (nums.length -1) ;<n>            return ans;<n>    }<n><n>    public static void main(String[] args) {<n>        int[] nums = {-9,-19,60,60,93,-5};<n>        System.out.println(new Solution().findTargetSumWays(nums, 90));<n><n>        int[] num1 = {-9, 60, 60};<n>        int[] num2 = {60, 61};<n>        System.err.println(new Solution()<n>               .findTargetSumWays2(num1, num2));<n><n>        int a = 1, b = 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:She loved buying products, she was driven by her what to shop more than any practical needs? Choices:  A: desire B: money C: time D: credit E: spending money<n>Output:		c - > i don't know. i haven't thought it through yet.<n><n><strong>Solution:</strong><n>Because at the very least, one must have spending money even if he doesn't have other reasons.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:A person lived in my what? Choices:  A: demonstration B: conference C: building D: garage E: mouth<n>Output:		"moth"<n><n>Input: How to be more famous? Choices: 1. Sing 2. Act on play 3. Write a book 4. Be a good basketball player 5. Make a popular blog 6. Be a great dancer 7. Make a TV show 8. Make a web site 9. Be a great singer 10. Be a model<n>Output:  Singing, being an actor, writing a book, making basketball, making your blog, dancing, making a television show, making a website, making a singer, the model <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:If you're speaking to a lawyer about getting a divorce, what relationship status are you trying to end? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:How do geese normally get from place to place? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Sam went to Paris where he ordered a blowfish at a sushi place. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What will happen to skin pinched in something? Choices:  A: feel cold B: feel pressure C: feel bumpy D: itches E: feel clammy<n>Output:		I think that when a human pinches his skin, he (1) feels cold.<n><n>Input: A man drove 270 mi. to get to a restaurant. On the way he saw two signs, one 100 mi. to his left and another 180 mi. to his far left. He also saw a sign 110 mi. to his right, and another 210 mi. to the right. What is the name of the restaurant where he ate lunch? A. The Taco Restaurant in Cincinnati B. The Arctic C. The Tavern in Miami D. The Crab Inn in San Francisco<n>Output: To start solving the puzzle, divide a distance between a man’s leftmost sign and his nearest sign by 100. The man saw signs 100 mi apart, so the answer to this sub-problem is 2/5. Now divide 2/5 by two, which will give you 0.4. Multiply it by 180 to get 72 mi; this is the exact distance your man needs to drive to reach his nearest sign. As he did not write down the signs, the last mile was the only part that he didn’t need. It was 270 – 72 = 198. The only town with that name that could have been reached in this amount of time was Cincinnati, which is where our man ate.<n><n>Input: At 500ft (150m) above the ground the acceleration of gravity is 5.0m/s/s. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Sally lost her kite because she wasn't careful. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The new play was the go to performance of the year, all the crowds would stand and what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What's it called when you have seen something through an eyepiece? Choices:  A: sights B: optical illusion C: optical telescope D: light microscope E: binocular<n>Output:		Answer:B. optic illusions are formed when one of the eyes is obscured or removed, or when one of the eyes produces a discrepant stimulus (e.g., one eye is damaged, stabbed, or has an abnormal focus or color sensitivity)<n><n>Input:Why did the boy cross the road?<n><n><n><n>Input:A pond.<n><n>Input:The moon.<n><n> Input: A ball.<n><n>Input:What kind of person would wear this?<n> Output:Answer:B. The sunglasses protect the person from damage that may be caused by the sun's ultraviolet (UV) radiation. The three animals are not birds.Bats are mammals, but they are not birds (because they do not fly). A giraffe is both a mammal and a bird.<n><n><n>Input:How can you use a microscope to see small creatures?Chose the right answer from the list below:<n><n>Output:Answer:A. Choices:A: 4/10 B: 5/10 C: 6/10 D: 9/10 E: 11/10<n>Output:it is known that there are ten red marbles and nine white marbles. for ten total and for nine white ones, there are 45 ways of selecting a total of nine white ones. so the probability of selecting all the nine white ones is 45/100 = 45% and for the rest of them the probability is 1/10 for any given outcome then there is a 45/15 chance of selection since each of the 10 possible selections is independent of the others, we multiply by 45/1. since there are ten possibilities for each white marble and there are a total of ten white marbles, there are 400 ways of choosing no white marbles. from this, we find that the probability for green marbles is 45/400 = 4. 5%.<n><n>Input:A person has the option of choosing the first, second, third, and fourth floors of a certain skyscraper. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What is necessary for learning by yourself? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:James complained that Alexa's electric guitar was too loud and he couldn't get any work done at home,  so she decided that she should get an acoustic guitar. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where must one wear a white shoe? Choices:  A: wedding B: tennis C: closet D: left foot E: house<n>Output:		A and E, answer: A and E<n><n>Question 1.What should not put in a bag for the weekend?<n><n>Solution-Do not put eggs in the backpack as a bag. answer: Do not put eggs in the bag<n><n>Question 2. Where must one wear a white shoes?<n><n>Solution: Wedding answer: A<n><n>Question 3. Who does the doctor prescribe the medication?<n><n>Solution:--A nurse answer: A<n><n><n>Question 8.Who's not allowed to sit in the park?<n><n>Solution---Children answer: C<n><n>#import math<n>solve = lambda a,b : math.floor(a / b)<n><n>def solution(n):<n>    a, b = [], []<n>    k = n // 2<n>    for i in range(k,n,2):<n>        a.append(i)<n>    for i in reversed(range(1, int(n / 2))):<n>        b.append(i)  <n>    <n>    return solve(a, b)<n>    
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:James chose to not to print the cards, because he wanted to be more personal. What speed do they have to travel separately in order for each man to arrive on the same time?<n>Output:Let the distance b - a be d,  The 120 km = d + d, Let the 1st and 2nd man speed be s1 and s2 respectively. When they move together, t1 t2 - s1 s2 and when they move separately, t1 = d/s1 - 20 and t2 = d/s2 - 20.<n>Hence, the required speed is d/ [s1 + s2] -20.<n>### Instraction:A person is working at a firm. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:John enjoyed his time visiting the museum. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What emotion do people expressing themselves show when they trip in front of a crowd and break their leg? Choices:  A: communication B: suffering C: pain D: laughter E: embarrassment<n>Output:		The correct answer is B.<n><n>Input:You are a programmer. There is a very important job of yours to accomplish. D: Simplify \ frac { 242 } { 9 }.<n>Output:B.<n><n>1+2=32 7+7+7=21 1+2+3+5=12 9+12=21 7+7+8=22 6+9=15 5+6+3+9=23 4+5+6+7=22 <n><n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the multiple choice question.<n>Input:A father and a mother each have a child.What is the chance that the child has brown eyes? We want to solve the following two equations:<n><n>\[{\begin{cases} {\frac{d}{b-c}}=(18)\\\frac{d}{b+c}=6\end{cases}}.\]<n><n>By subtraction, \(c=12\) and we can thus write the following equation:<n><n>\[d=\left(18-(12)\right)d+\left(6-(12)\right)=\left(18-9\right)d=\left(9\right)d.\]<n><n>From here, we will note that \(\frac{d}{\left(9\right)}\) must be our answer.<n><n>### Solution: 8<n><n>Let x be equal to the distance between buses.<n><n>The distance between the buses every 18 minutes is x.<n><n>The distance covered by the cyclist is 1.<n><n>The bus overtook the cyclist.<n><n>By rearranging the above equations.<n><n>We get<n><n>x = 1 + 12 x = (12 - 1) x = (11) x = 11 x<n><n>### Solution : 8<n><n>Suppose you have an arrangement with 3 beds. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Bob thought that his Pokemon cards were common and worthless, but he was wrong about them. Choices:  A: personal B: special C: shiny D: rare E: irregular<n>Output:		<n><n>### Input: ( ) The car's tyres are in very good condition( ) The car has a new oil change<n><n>### Answer:<n>Tyres : 6507<n><n>### Answer<n><n>### Input :A 2 digit number is divided by 5 and the reminder is 2.<n><n>Output Answer:<n>58 → 1<n><n>### Input Number:1036<n>Output Answer: 738<n><n>### Input a 2D array with 3 rows and 3 columns<n><n>Output a 2D array as 1 row and 1 column<n><n>### Input the number of integers (n) that can be written in base b (given that 0 < b < 10), excluding 0<n>for example, there are 3 integers in base 8 : 0,7 and 1<n>thus the answer is 3.<n><n>### Input 2 integers, a and b<n>Output sum(a+b)<n><n>### Input<n>  b  = 4000<n>  a  = 3999<n><n>Output<n> 4000-3999<n>### Input<n><n>5064<n>### Output<n>21

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What would an adult man do to get ready for work? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Mom is tidying a house, where would she put the loose dictionary? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Simon bought a cow because he wanted to put it to work.   He didn't want any meat for it.  Where might Simon be taking the cow? Choices:  A: countryside B: city C: dairy farm D: butcher shop E: canada<n>Output:		The correct answer is the city. Simon is clearly going to have to take the cow to a location that needs his cow to do some kind of work. He does not want to keep the cow itself for meat or dairy, so he cannot use the butcher shop or the dairy farm answers. He likely does not want to sell the cow, either, since he wants to put it to work, which eliminates choice B. That leaves the city and the countryside as the primary options for what he might do with the cow. Of those two choices, Simon would want to take the cow to the city rather than the countryside, since it is obvious that cows produce milk in the countryside. Choice D does not work for Simon as it is a butchershop, not a place to actually use the cow for work rather than to sell it for meat. So, choice E is the answer to this problem.<n><n>Input: the price of a pack of gum is 50 cents . the total of 15 packs of gum costs 75 dollars  . how much does each packe of gum cost? a b c d e<n><n>Output: The correct answers are A, B, C, and E.<n><n>

Choices:  A: accompaniment to meal B: waitress C: cafeteria D: home E: menu<n>Output:		I think we should be able to figure this one out together. I'm hungry. So let's find where in the menu I can find milk. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What could contain no more than around 100 people? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:John just made first violin. Choices:  A: violin case B: symphony orchestra C: class D: learning to play violin E: music store<n>Output:		Choice C: John made first position, but not in a violin.<n>### If this  task is not clear, please contact me for clarification<n><n>![Instruction](https://github.com/wbhz/GRE-instructions/raw/main/img/gre-instructions-for-new-students.png<n><n>![Instruction2](https://github. com/wbhz /GRE-instruc tions/raw/ main/ img/gre-instruc tio n for new students. PNG )
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where can someone keep a digital file? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Jimmy wanted a beer but his wife was an alcoholic on probation. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:what can years of playing tennis lead to? Choices:  A: tennis elbow B: proffesional player C: exercise D: victory E: becoming tired<n>Output:		Proffesional player or tennis elbow. After five hours the last digit of this number is equal to 14. What is the number?<n>Answer: 5140
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where would you be going if using a parking lot near a roller coaster? Hence the answer can be a parking lot near an amusement park.<n><n>Input: You are about to take a trip with ten friends. You have one hundred dollars to spend in local currency. Hence in this case 2 or 6 people can get a non-zero thing and 4 can get 0 items<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:A shop will give you what for your purchases? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The obsessive man was always washing hands, he had even done it so much once that it caused a what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where might I find unusual varieties of roses? Choices:  A: botanic garden B: flower garden C: backyard D: supermarket E: outdoors<n>Output:		The answer is B:<n><n>Input: A group of students is making a movie. They decide that the film should start with a scene taken somewhere in the mountains. Which of the following mountains should they pick?<n><n>A. Mount Rushmore<n>B. Haleakalā<n>C. Mount Kilimanjaro<n>D. Mount Fujiyama<n><n>Output: D:<n><n>There are 18 possible answers. It is possible that only one of the possible answers is the only valid answer. However, all the others may not have any effect on the rest of the program. For example, the correct answer to the second question may not necessarily be correct for the first question.<n><n>A program will be evaluated on this basis. Write a program that can answer these questions.<n><n><n><n>###### Python Solution<n><n>```<n>import math<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def busTime(self, b, B):<n>        """<n>        :type b: int<n>        :type B: int<n>        :rtype: int<n>        """<n>        return math.ceil(  math.ceil(b * B)  -  math.ceil(B * b) )<n>```<n><n>###### Output Screenshot<n><n><img style="width:600px;height:400px" src="busTime.png"/> <n><n><n>###### Summary <n>The idea is to first find the maximum distance between buses traveling at same speed in two different directions, and then find the interval for those buses by dividing the maximum (longest) duration by the speed.<n>

(A) July 24th<n>Output:(B) Wednesday the 24th July<n><n>Input:The formula for the area of a rectangle is A = lw where l is the length and w is the width.<n>Its most useful to measure the cost ($/ft2) of a rectangle by the area it covers (ft2).<n>We can set that up with the formula: C = lw * c where: C = cost ($/ft2), l = length (ft).<n>To find the cost of l (ft2) of the rectangle, plug in w and c, and solve for l like this: C = lw (c)/(w) C * w = lw (c) <n>(lw * c)/(w) = lw/w  = l C * w = l (w) = l <n>Solve for l again with w and c, now substituting in for l and solve: l = (w * c) / (w * c) l = (w *c ) / l = c w <n>So we can figure the cost of one foot of the window to be: C = (W * c) / (l) <n>( l * w)*(c)=C (l)(w)*c=C<n>Input:Find the volume of a sphere: S r= 4 l 3, where r is the radius, and l the length of an edge around the sphere. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where would a ficus plant brighten up a room? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:An electronics store had things damaged from the rain, where should these things be stored? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Having a car in the city seemed to be more trouble than it was worth, the man still had to walk to and from the what after commuting? Choices:  A: reverse B: backwards C: back and D: back and E: tally back<n>Output:		back<n><n>Input:How good are your skills and how you like , answers choices  A: I am very good <n>B: I am very bad C: I am average D: I like  A:  I do not like <n>B:  I am indifferent for <n>C:  This game is funny D:  not sure the best answer  : i like A<n><n><n><n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where do most people keep magazines? The fleas are known as parasites because they depend on their hosts (e.g. cats, dogs, rats, humans) for food and development. While the male flea does not bite or feed he moves back and forth on the host. The laying egg’s diet is blood, while the pupae are more active after coming out of their cocoons, and then go to their next host (e.g. cat, dog, etc.) to bite and continue the life cycle.<n><n><n>A: not a common choice.<n><n>B: False.<n><n>C: False.<n><n>E: not a common choice<n><n>The flea is an insects which is 2–4mm long. The flease are known as parasite because they depend on their host. The male fleas do not bite or feed. The female fleas live only for 30 days. They just live on the host and spend their time laying eggs. There are 600-800 eggs per female flea, so they lay eggs all throughout their lives on their hosts. The blood meals take up 3-8% of the entire blood sucking cycle. After sucking blood, the fleas spend more their time laying eggs compared to feeding. Since the fleas do not get blood on a regular basis, they usually travel on the host to find food. The female lay around 10-15% of the eggs they suck on the host. Even after all this eggs they still survive for only about 10 months. After all the eggs are laid, the adult flea is able to survive for only about two weeks.<n><n>1.False<n>  <n>2.True<n>  <n>3.False<n>  <n>4.True<n><n><n><n>### Instruction:How many positive 3 digit numbers are divisible by both 2 and 3 that do not have the digit 3 in them?<n><n>Input:951767<n>Output:23<n>  <n>### Instruction 1 : How many digits does 95176 have?<n>  <n>### # Instruction 2 : What is the largest number in 951776?<n><n>  <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where could you find a bookstore? Choices:  A: town B: carpeting C: city D: phone book E: magazines<n>Output:		the first line should be ‘A, B, C’.<n><n>Input: A: How heavy is a goldfish A: 0.1 B: 4 C: 3 lb D: 5lb E: 0.1 Kg<n>Output: The first line should be ‘E,K,A,D’.<n><n>Input; A: Where is my homework?<n><n>B: Right here in my bag<n>C: In the house<n>D: In the backpack<n>E: At the station<n><n>Output: The first should be ‘E,E,B’<n><n>Input: a b c -> 1 2 3

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Where would you put a handle if you want to bring it with you? Choices:  A: briefcase B: coffee cup C: carry object D: frying pan E: on a hat<n>Output:		 D<n>Explanation: When you use a handle to carry an object, it is necessary to consider not only the weight of the object but also the way it is carried. For example, the handle on a handle bag is not used to carry weight but for walking. In the given question, there are three choices A, C and E, which do not consider the way it should be used. Choice B and D describe the way, which is the same as a general handle. So we should choose D if we want to bring it with us.<n><n>Instruction:Please choose the most likely answer.<n><n>Input:a farmer has 6 sheep and sells all 6 sheep for $150. 1 sheep is sold at $25 less than another, which was sold for $20 more than that. Which is the one sold for less money? a ) The cheapest sheep b ) The third cheapest sheep c ) The fourth cheapest sheep d ) All sheep are equally cheap, that is to say, they have the same price.<n>Output:  This question has several meanings but it is ambiguous which one is asked. To solve this problem, let's take a look at the possible meanings first. Suppose there are three sheep with different prices, they are A, B and C. A is cheaper, B is more expensive, C is equally expensive. If it is asked to find B, then this answer is A, B, C ; if it is asked to find the "cheapest" sheep, then this answer is B, which is obviously more expensive than the "second cheapest sheep", C. Therefore, if an "individual" sheep is cheap when comparing that with other individual sheep, then it is also cheaper when comparing with another "individual sheep". Accordingly, if the "individual sheep" is more expensive when comparing with other "individual sheep", it is also more expensive when comparing with another " individual sheep". Therefore, if the "individually cheapest sheep" is "sold for $20 less than another", it must be that another sheep sold for " $25 more than the "individually most expensive sheep". That is to say, the most expensive sheep among the "six sheep" must be the one sold for " $20 more than another". From an another perspective, this question is also very similar to the case when s
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What do you need to have before buying products? Choices:  A: desire B: spending money C: money D: needs E: time<n>Output:		Desire, Spending Money<n>Solution:Input the correct answer<n>### Instruction:Answer the question.<n>If we have 15 marbles each has 2 different colored marbles choose 12 marbles and leave 8 different colored marbles in the bowl, how many of the 8 different colored ones can you pick up?<n>Output:Let the number of red marbles in the bowls be'r ', then'r'is in the range [1, 9] Let the number of different coloured(non-red) marbles in the bowel be'd ',then'd'is in the range(35, 51]<n>(Therefore'r '>=1 and'r '<=9 and'd'>=35 and'd '<=51 )<n>The total of'r'and'd'cannot exceed the 15 marbles. Therefore, 2'r'+'d' cannot exceed 15. The number of different colored marbles can be 15+2''r''- 'd'and'd'is the range(35,51] therefore the answer is : the number of different colored marble varies (between 1 +'(2'r'- 'd ') and 1 +2 'r'.<n><n>###Instruction:answer the question.<n>2 friends, 4 fruits, and 10 minutes: how can they share?<n>Output:10 bananas 10 pineapples 2 each of other fruits

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:A person takes a seat to watch a movie, where is he? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What is love when everyone keeps feeling it? Choices: <n><n><n>2 a. My father.<n>3 b. My parents.<n>4 c. My mother.<n>5 d. Any of them.<n>Output:Choices:: <n><n><n>2 c.<n><n><n>Input:Who did you like? <n><n><n>Output:Me.<n><n>Input:What did you do? Choices:  a. Favor b. Effort c. Work d. Opportunity Output:Choices: <n><n>3 b.<n><n>Input:Do you have a dog? <n><n>Output:No.<n>Input:Who has more? Choices: 2 a. 1 b. 2021 c. 23 d. 13 2021 220 2421 Output:Choices: a<n><n>Input:Who will be the winner? Choices: 3 a. No one b. My friend c. I d. I hope so Output:Choices:<n><n>1. a<n><n>input:The name of my friends? Choices:: 2. Aaron 3. Ashutosh 4. Ankush 5. Arushi 6. Anuraag 7. Akshat 8. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:A balloon or two is a staple at a what? Choices:  A: birthday party B: child's hand C: grocery store D: sky E: up in the<n>Output:		A balloon is a staple on a Birthday Party.<n>Answer:A Balloon is a stape on a Birthday party<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The man needed balls of cotton, where should he look? Choices:  A: south B: georgia C: north carolina D: pocket E: medicine cabinet<n>Output:		The answer is D.<n><n>Input: A doctor needed a vacation. Where should he go? Choices:<n><n><n>A: Chicago B: Texas C: South Africa D: Tierra del Fuego E: Antarctica<n><n>Output: The answer choices are A, B, C, and D. The doctor needs to go to Antarctica because it is in the same time zone as his practice.<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:If you're traveling along a highway what item made of paper can you use to find your way? So you should never use it.<n><n>Input: If you go to a foreign city you should bring a: B: guidebook C: map D: atlas E: all of them<n>Output: A: you should never bring a guidebook because you will be taken to the city by google. Also google knows where your going so you do not even have to bring a map, just trust in google to guide you there.<n><n>Input:How big is an octopuses brain? A 10 year old is born B 10 million neurons is born C 175 neurons are grown D 5000 neurons are grown<n>Output:D: The octopus has 27,000 small neurons.<n><n>Input:What is the formula for the density of a square prism? A 0.048 A2 B 36A C 12.8A D 7.5 A2<n>Output:A: Formula for cube volume:  volume =  length × width × height For a cuboid, Volume = base area × height  If height is equal to 1, then Cube = Lwh <n>The volume of the prism = Length × width × height  Now density = mass / volume  Density = mass × g  So Density = m / (wh)  If length and width are equal, then wh= A 2  mass = m A 2  × g A 2  wh  = (L² × W²)/ A 2  A 2  × Wh = m × G <n>So Density = (w × length)/A 2  or Density = (Volume/Area)  Density = (L × W)/A <n>Thus for Square prism density = volume/ area of 2  Density = 0.04 <n><n>Input: What is an ideal solution? And<n>if its length is less than one,then it is not a valid string.<n>\item When the string is more than one the logic is :<n>\end{itemize}<n><n>"madam" is one word, and it is a Palindrome<n>\begin{itemize}\item If the letter is greater than or equal to 'Z' then it is a alphabet,otherwise it is not an alphabet.<n>\item If the letter is a alphabet then the alphabet is
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:John's RV needs electricity so that he can cook lunch.  Where would he go to plug in? Choices:  A: toy store B: basement C: school D: rest area E: building<n>Output:		<n>If he can plug in at the building, then the probability is P(A)<n>If the building is not available, then the probability would become P(B) (because there is only one other choice)<n>Since it must be possible if available, then the two choices in the first two cases must be exclusive, so P(B) must be half that of P(A).<n>So, (P(B)/P(A)) = 1/2<n>And, since probability is a ratio, we can say:<n><n>P(A) = 1/2 * ((1/2)^2)^ (1 divided by 2n)<n>P(B) = 1/4 * ((1/2^0)^ (1 divided by n)<n>Substituting this into <n><n>P ( A or B) = 2/4 = 1<n><n>So the probability of John being able to find something is 1.<n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:Johnny and bill fought over money. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:The man took 3 hours every morning for grooming, what is the likely result with his job? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: a man cycling along the road noticed that every 18 minutes a bus overtakes him and every 6 minutes he meets an oncoming bus. if all buses and the cyclist move at a constant speed, what is the time interval between consecutive buses? a ) 5 minutes, b ) 6 minutes, c ) 8 minutes, d ) 9 minutes, e ) 10 minutes<n>Output: let's say the distance between the buses is d. we want to determine interval = \ frac { d } { b }, where b is the speed of bus. let the speed of cyclist be c. every 18 minutes a bus overtakes cyclist : \ frac { d } { b - c } = 18, d = 18 b - 18 c ; every 6 minutes cyclist meets an oncoming bus : \ frac { d } { b + c } = 6, d = 6 b + 6 c ; d = 18 b - 18 c = 6 b + 6 c, - - > b = 2 c, - - > d = 18 b - 9 b = 9 b. interval = \ frac { d } { b } = \ frac { 9 b } { b } = 9 answer : d ( 9 minutes ).<n>So the final answer is d<n><n>Input:What European country is famous for its potato industry? Choices:  A: idaho B: casserole C: new hampshire D: root cellar E: ireland<n>Output:		a <n><n>#### Solution<n>Here we just need to check the sum of total time and total number using brute force logic and find the minimum. Brute force means going through all possible values and then calculating. <n>We can also implement this program in O(n) time using dynamic programing. Which is 15% faster.<n>We can also do this using recurrence relation. But it should only be used if time complexity of the problem is O(n). If we apply recursion O(n^2) we will have to go through all the elements.<n>For the above question answer is c. New Hampshire is a very famous potato producing state.<n>```<n><n>#### DFS<n>This is the solution provided by google.<n><n>```cpp<n>// Write your code here<n><n>typedef long long l;<n>// Given array of length n<n>l time[9009] = {0};<n>l size[9009], n;<n>// Read size from input<n>cin >> size >> n;<n>// Sum of time taken to complete ith task<n>l sum = size[0];<n>// Initialising values for DFS of task<n>for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){<n>	sum += time[i]; <n>	l tmp = sum;<n>	// Calling DFS<n>	dfs(0, tmp, i);<n>}<n>// DFS of task<n>// Calucate difference in size from first and second task<n>l d = time[1] - time[0];<n>// Print the difference<n>if(d > time[size.size()-1]-1){<n>	cout << "Solution = " << d - (time[size.size() - 1] - 1) <<endl;<n>}<n>else{<n>	cout << "no solution" << endl;<n>}<n>// Difference is more than task size<n>dfs(0, 0, 0); // time[0] can only be first task<n>```<n><n>## Time Constraints<n>I.E.
